git-changelog

  Generate a human-readable change log from git.
  
  This bash script lets you generate a human readable change log from your git
  repository.
  
  It requires that you:
  - Create git tags for the different versions of your code.
  - Format the commit messages for commits you wish to include in the change
  log, in the same way you format a markdown bullet, by prefixing it with a
  hyphen and a space ("- ").

Usage:
  git-changelog [OPTIONS]
  git-changelog --help | -h
  git-changelog --version | -v

Options:
  --tail, -t N
    Show only the last N tags.

  --reverse, -r
    Show tags in reverse order (newest first).

  --out, -o PATH
    Save output to a file.

  --color, -c MODE
    Enable or disable color. Supported modes:
    - `yes`, `on`, `always`
    - `no`, `off`, `never`
    - `auto`
    Default: auto

  --save, -s
    Shortcut for `--reverse --out CHANGELOG.md`.

  -1
    Shortcut for `--tail 1`.

  -2
    Shortcut for `--tail 2`.

  --help, -h
    Show this help

  --version, -v
    Show version number

Examples:
  git changelog --tail 3
  git changelog --out CHANGELOG.md
  git changelog -r -o CHANGELOG.md
